 Canet, the name of several places in Catalonia (Spain) and France, named with this word.","French: nickname meaning ‘little duck’ in Old French, perhaps applied to someone thought to resemble a duck in some way or to a dealer in poultry."],"variants":[{"name":"Canete","meanings":["Spanish (<b>Cañete</b>): habitational name (of the same etymology as   Canet  ) from any of the places called Cañete, especially Cañete de las Torres (Seville), Cañete la Real (Málaga) and Cañete (Cuenca)."]}]},{"name":"Emma","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of compound names such as   Ermintrude   containing the word <i>erm(en)</i>, <i>irm(en)</i> ‘entire’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, but its popularity in medieval England was greatly enhanced by the fact that it had been borne by the mother of Edward the Confessor, herself a Norman. In modern times, it was only in moderate use early in the 20th century but rose sharply in favour in the 1970s and has since remained perennially popular."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":6,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Emma Agnes Capet was born in 1060, in Norfolk, England. She married Robert Daisnel I about 1081, in Norfolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died on 16 April 1085, in Paris, Île-de-France, France, at the age of 25."},"et":{"1060–10 Apr 1085":"1060–16. aprill 1085","1058–Male":"1058–Surnud","1082–1112":"1082–1112","1060–1085":"1060–1085","um 1081":"umbes 1081","1058":"1058","1112":"1112","10 Apr 1085":"16. aprill 1085","1066":"1066","1085":"1085","1060":"1060","1082":"1082","Burgh Next Aylsham, Norfolk, England":"Burgh next Aylsham, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Paris, Île-de-France, France":"Paris, Île-de-France, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1060–10 Apr 1085":"1060–16. huhtikuuta 1085","1058–Male":"1058–Kuollut","1082–1112":"1082–1112","1060–1085":"1060–1085","um 1081":"noin 1081","1058":"1058","1112":"1112","10 Apr 1085":"16. huhtikuuta 1085","1066":"1066","1085":"1085","1060":"1060","1082":"1082","Burgh Next Aylsham, Norfolk, England":"Burgh next Aylsham, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Paris, Île-de-France, France":"Paris, Île-de-France, Ranska"},"fr":{"1060–10 Apr 1085":"1060–16 avril 1085","1058–Male":"1058–Décédé","1082–1112":"1082–1112","1060–1085":"1060–1085","um 1081":"environ 1081","1058":"1058","111